Roots TV Nigeria founder Dumebi Kachikwu has won the presidential ticket of the African Democratic Congress (ADC) with 978 votes. Kachikwu, who hails from Anioma extraction of Delta State, defeated his main challenger and one+ time Deputy Governor of Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) Prof. Kingsley Moghalu, who polled 589 votes. Moghalu, who contested for the 2019 presidency, came second at the primary. Other aspirants in the race include a person with special needs, Dr. Chike Okogwu, who stepped down and Dr Chukwuka Monye who scored 339 votes while Princess Chichi Ojei polled 72 votes.   2023: It’s Tinubu vs. Atiku     Delegates laud APC for free, fair credible primary election     ‘APC Sokoto House of Reps candidate will deliver’   A total of 2,040 delegates were accredited and participated in the presidential primary held within the Marque wing of the sprawling Olusegun Obasanjo Presidential Library(OOPL), Abeokuta, the Ogun state capital. The National Chairman of the party, Chief Ralph Nwosu, lamented the deterioration in many areas of the nation’s life due to what he called leadership failure by the All Progressives Congress(APC) and People’s Democratic Party (PDP.) Nwosu said the party was aiming to produce 75 percent of lawmakers at the State and Federal levels. He stated the lawmakers would make quality laws that will benefit Nigerians and not for the few.